Oh, you were almost correctly.
If you see, this `codeRegister` returns an object. There's a variable called `pw`. You can do that:
```php
$codeRegister = $w->codeRegister( '123456' );
var_dump( $codeRegister ); 
```
You will see all the object, and there will be your password. Exemple:
```php
object(stdClass)[9]
  public 'status' => string 'ok' (length=2)
  public 'login' => string '55xxxxxxxxx070' (length=13)
  public 'pw' => string '0lvxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx1E=' (length=28)
  public 'type' => string 'existing' (length=8)
  public 'expiration' => int 1443256747
  public 'kind' => string 'free' (length=4)
  public 'price' => string 'US$0.99' (length=7)
  public 'cost' => string '0.99' (length=4)
  public 'currency' => string 'USD' (length=3)
  public 'price_expiration' => int 1414897682
```
Now that you have your password, you can do whatever you want in the API. Just configure the settings. Oh, and remember that identity you can keep empty.

